The Dutch alphabet uses the same 26 letters as English, but some letters and combinations are pronounced quite differently. Here’s a clear guide to each letter with approximate pronunciation (using English-like hints):


---

Dutch Alphabet & Pronunciation

A – “ah” (like a in “father”)
B – “bay”
C – “say” (before e/i/y), or “kay” (before a/o/u)
D – “day” (often softer at the end of words, like “t”)
E – “uh” (short), or “ay” (long, like in “say”)
F – “ef”
G – harsh throaty sound (like clearing your throat, not in English)
H – “hah”
I – “ih” (like i in “sit”)
J – “yay” (like English “y”)
K – “kah”
L – “el”
M – “em”
N – “en”
O – “oh” (short or long depending on word)
P – “pay”
Q – “kew” (rare, mostly in loanwords)
R – rolled or guttural (varies by region)
S – “es”
T – “tay”
U – rounded front vowel (no exact English equivalent; like saying “ee” with rounded lips)
V – between “v” and “f”
W – between English “w” and “v” (closer to “v”)
X – “iks”
Y – “ij” sound (see below)
Z – “zet” (like “z” in “zoo,” but softer)


---

Important Dutch Letter Combinations

These are crucial because Dutch relies heavily on them:

IJ / EI – sound like “eye”

OU / AU – like “ow” in “cow”

EU – like French “eu” (no exact English equivalent; similar to “uh” with rounded lips)

UI – unique Dutch sound (somewhere between “ow” and “uh,” tricky for beginners)

CH / G – harsh throat sound

SCH – “s” + harsh “g” sound

NG – like “ng” in “sing”



---

A quick tip

Dutch pronunciation depends a lot on vowel length and combinations, more than single letters alone. So once you learn these combos, your pronunciation improves fast.


